Phase 2 doubts / clarifications

- Source priority for factual enrichment is not explicitly defined in the provided docs.
  Context confirms the sources and their roles: manual override/CMS, official website,
  Google Places, Wikidata, Reviews API/CMS, and Viator/raw supplier feed. Proposed
  implementation order is: manual override > official website > Google Places >
  Wikidata > Viator.

Confirmed Phase 2 test entities:

- Rome
- Colosseum
- Vatican Museums
- Paris
- Eiffel Tower

Confirmed Google Places behavior:

- If GOOGLE_PLACES_API_KEY exists, use live Google Places.
- If GOOGLE_PLACES_API_KEY is missing, use deterministic stub mode.
- No separate live-mode feature flag is required for the POC.

Confirmed manual override scope:

- Add manual override support in the Phase 2 data/API layer.
- Do not build an admin UI in this POC phase.

Confirmed rating handling:

- Store Google Places rating and review_count as external place facts in EnrichedFact.
- Keep internal Rosotravel verified review aggregates as a separate future concern.
- Do not mix Google place ratings with internal AggregateRating schema values.

Factual refresh schedule ambiguity:

- Docs define factual_hash and say factual changes trigger schema refresh, not AI
  regeneration by default.
- WBS explicitly defines nightly refresh for review/proof aggregates.
- Docs do not clearly define the refresh cadence for Google Places/Wikidata facts.
- POC decision: facts refresh manually when the enrich endpoint is called.

Confirmed official website handling:

- Store official_website in enriched facts when available.
- Include official_website in factual_hash.
- Expose official_website via the facts endpoint.

Phase 3 LLM provider clarification:

- Phase 3 plan mentions OPENAI_API_KEY for live GPT output.
- User provided a Groq API key and asked to try/use a Groq model.
- Implementation should support Groq via its OpenAI-compatible Chat Completions API.
- Use stub/template mode when GROQ_API_KEY is not configured.

Phase 4 Model C ambiguities / POC assumptions:

- Docs clearly define RAW > Pool > Set and say Set requires manual confirmation, but the
  exact production UI/workflow for Product Ops confirmation is not specified. POC should expose
  an API endpoint to simulate this.
- Docs define quality floors in several places, but the current POC product fixtures do not have
  all production fields such as INSTANT confirmation, fulfillment status, cancellation quality,
  language availability, verified review themes, or supplier reliability. POC quality scoring must
  use available fields only.
- Docs require archetype/core-vs-variant grouping and near-duplicate avoidance, but no exact
  taxonomy file is provided. POC should derive lightweight archetypes from category_group and
  title keywords.
- Docs reference product_attraction_relations for POI picks, but the current POC does not yet
  store product-to-attraction relation records. City-level picks can be implemented now; POI-level
  picks need relation data later.
- Docs say DEE may reorder within precomputed Set outputs and must not introduce products outside
  Set, but the exact audience signal source/confidence model is not provided. POC should return
  deterministic default ordering only, with structure ready for audience-aware ordering later.

Phase 5 schema/publishing POC assumptions:

- Docs require canonical URLs but do not provide the final production URL builder/base domain for
  this POC. Use deterministic POC canonicals under https://www.rosotravel.com/en/... and keep the
  builder centralized for replacement later.
- Docs require UI-to-schema parity, but this backend POC has no rendered frontend. Treat content
  included in PublishedRecord.content as the visible UI snapshot, and include FAQ/ItemList/rating
  schema only when that snapshot contains the matching block/source.
- Docs require JSON-LD validation against schema.org; POC validation should perform structural and
  traceability checks locally, not call an external validator.

Phase 6 visibility/MCP POC assumption:

- Docs call this an MCP server, but the phase plan explicitly allows plain REST endpoints first.
  POC should implement the functional contract under /mcp/* now, with a real JSON-RPC/MCP
  transport wrapper left as a follow-up decision.

Phase 7 SQL / persistence local setup:

- Docs require persistence, but do not prescribe the local development database provisioning flow.
- POC decision: create a local Docker PostgreSQL 16 container named roso-postgres, keep SQLite as
  the zero-config fallback in .env.example, and switch real local runs through DATABASE_URL.

Phase 7 Viator live ingestion assumption:

- Viator products reference destination taxonomy IDs. If the referenced destination has not been
  ingested locally yet, POC product ingestion keeps viator_primary_destination_id in the raw payload
  but leaves the relational destination_entity_id unset to avoid failing the product import.

Phase 7 SEMrush keyword intelligence assumption:

- Docs require keyword volume/intent/PAA style inputs, but do not specify exact target markets per
  entity. POC default is SEMRUSH_DATABASE=us, overridable per request with the database query param.
- SEMrush returns SEO API reports as CSV. POC stores normalized related keywords and phrase
  questions, then includes the latest stored keyword intel in drafting context.

Phase 7 vector similarity decision:

- User decided not to use Qdrant for the POC. Use Postgres pgvector plus local sentence-transformer
  embeddings for the duplicate/similarity gate.
- The first local Postgres container was based on postgres:16 and did not include pgvector. POC
  keeps it untouched and uses a separate pgvector-enabled container named roso-pgvector on port
  5433.

City / country page publishing gap:

- Docs explicitly define City Page and Country Page surfaces. Earlier POC work exposed city/country
  Model C API rollups but did not publish dedicated landing page records.
- POC decision: city/country pages are backend PublishedRecord rows first. Frontend routes/templates
  can consume the same published payloads later.
